Yeah, Richardson&#39;s model is a very clear progression and relates mostly
to uris and methods. Which actually the more i think about it is
lacking as REST is much more than that.

In this case i wonder if a point based scoring system would be better.
In particular because we are talking about how well the fwk supports
REST rather than the system itself that uses it.

Sent from my Windows Phone
From: Markus Lanthaler
Sent: 4/6/2012 9:36 PM
To: rest-discuss@yahoogroups.com
Subject: RE: [rest-discuss] Evaluating REST Frameworks - Request for
feedback and help
Hi William,

Looks to be an interesting &quot;project&quot;.


&gt; Now, please bear in mind this is
&gt; not a competition, where higher level means that framework wins. As
&gt; stated in the article, even level 1 fully supports REST, only the
&gt; developer may need to do some extra work to get there. What we are
&gt; looking for is evaluating the frameworks in a way that helps the
&gt; framework makers and the users to identify the needs and solutions. It
&gt; is like suggesting a tool and testing it in the field for tuning.

It&#39;s quite normal that people use those levels as ranking. I think it would
make the intention much clearer if you would create a matrix instead of
using these (maturity) levels. So, e.g., framework X has support for routing
and media types whereas framework Y has hypermedia/semantics support.

You can&#39;t do that that easily with levels. Framework X is on level 3 and 5??
Is it then also on 4? What about 1 and 2 then? But maybe it&#39;s too late to
change that as the article has already been published..



